o control.  The higher level your guild is the more you understand this.  Most encounters revolve around Chealing a main tank who everyone works to keep the MOB focused on.  This tank needs to have very high Armor Class, be buffed to the teeth and have the highest possible taunting weapons.  The recipes for this are endless but for the sake or argument a 60 warrior with EPICS and full warlord from ToV is a nice front man.<br><br>In order to fully equip such a warrior you will spend man many trips in ToV and endless work to get the components for the weapons.  Since most guilds have multiple classes you will have to make the following decision.<br><br>a: Do we focus our energy on equipping one warrior so that we can do the Uber encounters sooner.<br><br>b. Do we split loot and sacrifice AC an Taunt on out Master Assist to even out the warrior classes in our guild.<br><br>In Methods of Madness we went the A route about four times.<br><br>Over time in each instance we have ended up either <br><br>a. Burning out the Master Assist who simply gets tired of being a required component of every single raid.  <br><br>B.  Discovered that that cute little warrior who showed up looking like a level 30 rogue equipped in things he found in Lower Guk refuse dispenser and was so incredibly grateful for his first real BP suddenly is not so loyal once fully equipped.<br><br>No single class is so dependant on gear as the warrior.  Maybe this is part of the reason that their interest in the game seems to wane when they get a level of gear to which their are few upgrades.  <br><br>I understand that killing all the named in ToV can upgrade them but I mean practical short term upgrades.<br><br>What I find is that suddenly this class tends to lose interest if they are not likely to receive upgrades and that this is manifested as an interst in doing something new. <br><br>My point here is that you may see a shortcut to Uberdom by having one superwarrior but in the long term dont be surprised if you end up doing this process two or three times which leaves you with one uber warrior when you could have managed it a bit differently and had three or four.<br><br>Please understand this is not a bash on the warrior class and I know good ethical warriors personally who really are grateful for the things the guild has done for them.  I have just found that in managing a guild with a lot of warriors and a lot of loot over the last couple years that short term solution are long term headaches.<br><br>Just my little nugget of Wisdom.<br><br>Extreme Measure<br>GM Methods of Madness<br>&quot;Incoming couple of blues&quot;<br>60 Necromancer <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/umentat1.showPublicProfile?language=EN>mentat 1</A> at: 1/16/02 11:10:37 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f7f7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/uctuttle.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ctuttle</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Indifferent Poster</span><br> <font color=#778899>(1/16/02 2:14:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub95.ezboard.com/finnoruukserverfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=216.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.somuchtuttle.com/pics/eq/dorimhead.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Lessons learned from MA equipping a large guild</span><hr size=1> Actually this is a pretty solid piece of advice. Thanks for sharing it. <p><center><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=29713"><img src="http://www.somuchtuttle.com/pics/eq/soulshieldbanner.jpg" border=0></center></a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f7f7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/uoderrybadgerclaw.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Oderry Badgerclaw</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Amiable Poster</span><br> <font color=#778899>(1/16/02 2:28: